      .setBranchesToClone(Arrays.asList(&quot;refs/heads/branch-name&quot;))
      .setBranch(&quot;refs/heads/branch-name&quot;)
      .call();
} catch (GitAPIException e) {
    System.err.println(&quot;Exception occurred while cloning repo.&quot;);
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

### Runtime exec

If you don&#39;t want the learning curve of using JGit, or don&#39;t want the external dependency, you can also call git commands using the [Runtime][3] `exec` method. This requires that git be installed, accessible and authenticated on the host OS. Here&#39;s an example:

```java
import java.io.*;

try {
    String cmd = &quot;git clone https://github.com/account/repo.git&quot;;
    Process p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
